I disagree. The proposed system concentrates and centralizes the power of big validators at the expense of small- and medium-size validators. Why not allowing delegation without deregistering the validators that don't make it to the top 100 (assuming that's the plan, of course)? 

Also, this shouldn't be about privileges, but about network decentralization (we are all for a solid decentralization of the network, right?) You  need 32 ETH to run an ETH validator, whether you supported Ethereum or not from the outset. And we know that even Ethereum is not an example of a decentralized network.

I don't want to come across as supportive of Keith's view, but many chains have a way of keeping an active validator set. It's not possible to have infinite amount being in active set. 

Whereas should it be about privilege? You're right, it shouldn't be and it may be ascribed to simply bring early enough to buy a lot on the cheap to muscle out competition.

As usual, open market wins, but it takes capital

to answer your question: because doing so would mean less delegate validation than the proposed system -- and delegate validating was made to fund the Bittensor Foundation moving forward... (the hope is that many will delegate stake to the Foundation validators to support Bittensor).

You can always ask team at next TGIFT the reasoning behind limiting valis - also the 100 number is not set in stone and is still being fleshed out.

No decision was ever made for “privileges”- people being super early has benefits in all projects- its just that simple- but we are still early
Delegation to fund the foundation is critical for network growth YES

We need teams building on their validator- validators need to be robust enough to query tasks quickly - this type of growth/building increases the end goal of being the largest decentralised neural network in the world
Bigger the validator - faster the queries
also, generally speaking, Bittensor must prioritize survival over rewarding of miners whether big or small... survival comes first... and the new validation mechanism serves to ensure it.
Also delegating funds other teams to build on the network

another way to look at it is, if you were mining BTC, there would be no staking... so any staking rewards is icing on the cake. is there going to be less icing for some? yes. what do we get in return? Bittensor Foundation having a reliable stream of funding moving forward... in a way that doesn't create obligations of particular entities giving it money to operate... (i.e. investment whether by VC or else)
If we want to see All MODALITIES being built used on Bittensor- we need lots of devs in the foundation- delegating to them will see so much value in the future growth of BITTENSOR - 😉
Its also hassle free - validating is easy but not set and forget - new people coming in will find delegating smooth and simple 🔥
So in that regard we are making it very inclusive 🤗
Just my 3c 😂🧚🏻‍♀️💜
